hire, England":"Bideford, Devon, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grenville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Grainville-la-Teinturière in Seine-Maritime, France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":21,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Archbishop William Grenville II was born in 1238, in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England, his father, Sir Richard de Grenville V, was 51 and his mother, Lady Jane Trewynt, was 29. He married Johanna WORTHAM in 1259, in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1260, in his hometown, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1238–1260":"1238–1260","12